SIMPLE: patient
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Patient
<hw>Pa"tient</hw> <pr>(p⟦amac⟧"sh⟦eit⟧nt)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.,
fr. L. <ets>patiens</ets>, <ets>-entis</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>pati</ets>
to suffer. Cf. <er>Pathos</er>, <er>Passion</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Having the quality of enduring; physically able to suffer or
bear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Patient</qex> of severest toil and hardship.</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Fell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Undergoing pains, trials, or the like, without
murmuring or fretfulness; bearing up with equanimity against trouble;
long-suffering.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Constant in pursuit or exertion; persevering; calmly
diligent; <as>as, <ex>patient</ex> endeavor</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whatever I have done is due to <qex>patient</qex> thought.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir I. Newton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Expectant with calmness, or without discontent; not
hasty; not overeager; composed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not <qex>patient</qex> to expect the turns of fate.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Forbearing; long-suffering.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be <qex>patient</qex> toward all men.</q> <rj><qau>1 Thess. v.
14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Patient</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Patient
<hw>Pa"tient</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that
which, is passively affected; a passive recipient.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Malice is a passion so impetuous and precipitate that it often
involves the agent and the <qex>patient</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Gov. of
Tongue.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person under medical or surgical treatment; --
correlative to <inv>physician</inv> or <inv>nurse</inv>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like a physician, . . . seeing his <qex>patient</qex> in a
pestilent fever.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>In patient</b></col>, <cd>a patient who receives lodging
and food, as treatment, in a hospital or an infirmary.</cd> --
<col><b>Out patient</b></col>, <cd>one who receives advice and medicine,
or treatment, from an infirmary.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Patient</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Patient
<hw>Pa"tient</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To compose, to calm.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Patient</xex> yourself, madam.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Patiently</ent>⟦br⟧
